               <msContents>
                  <summary>
                     The <title>Kulliyāt</title>, or collected works of Jalayirid-era panegyric poet Salmān Sāvajī (d. 1376). This 15th-century Timurid-era volume contains not only the author's <title>Dīvān</title>, but also his <title key="work_8419">Jamshīd and Khurshīd</title>, and <title>Dah'nāmah</title> (Ten Tales).
                  </summary>
                  <!-- Search for the other dated entry mentioned by Kerney-->
                  
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_76-item1">
                     <author key="person_36059765" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/36059765/">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Salmān Sāvajī, d. 1376</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">سلمان ساوجى</persName>
                     </author>
                     <editor role="scr">
                        <persName role="scr">‘Aṭā' Allāh ibn Shaykh ‘Alī</persName>
                     </editor>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20032" change="#ids-cleanup">Kulliyāt</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_20032" change="#ids-cleanup">کلیات</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmalla"><locus from="1b" to="1b">برگ ۱پ (Folio 1b):</locus>
                        هر دل که در هوای جمالش مجال یافت * عنقای همتش دو جهان زیر بال یافت.
                        </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="313a" to="313a">برگ ۳۱۳ر (Folio 313a):</locus>
                        همیشه روزگار پادشاه اسلام فرخ همایون باد و از نوایب و مصایب مصون و محروس بمحمد و آله الطاهرین.
                     </explicit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="287a" to="287a">برگ ۲۸۷ر (Folio 287a):</locus>
                        تمت الدیوان الصاحب الاعظم افتخار و املح الشعر العالم حسان الزمان سحبان البیان جمال الملة و الدین خواجه سلمان علیه الرحمة و الغفران علی ید العبد المحتاج الی فضل الله ابن الشیخ علي عطا الله فی یوم الاحد حادی عشرین سعبان المعظم سنه تسع و تسعین و سبعمایه.
                     </colophon>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="313a" to="313a">برگ ۳۱۳ر (Folio 313a):</locus>
                        تمت کتاب حدایق السحر فی علم الشعر علی ید العبد المحتاج الی فضل الله ابن الشیخ علي عطا الله اصلح الله شانه اللهم اغفر لکاتبه و لصاحبه و لقاریه و لمن نطرفیه امن برب العالمین.
                     </colophon>
                     <colophon>Two colophons, the first on folio <locus from="287a" to="287a">287a</locus> dated Sunday 21 Sha‘bān 799 (Jun.–Jul. 1607 CE), and another on
                        folio <locus from="313a" to="313a">313a</locus> for the volume's completion by the scribe <persName role="scr">‘Aṭā' Allāh ibn Shaykh ‘Alī</persName> in Jumādà II 1016 AH (Sep.–Oct. 1607 CE).
                     </colophon>
                     <note>For another copy of this manuscript held in the Rylands, see <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7328"><idno>Persian MS 820</idno></ref>.</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart"><support>Text block of ivoury-coloured, sized and polished <material>paper</material> likely handmade in <placeName cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000235">Greater Iran</placeName> </support>
                        <!-- flyleaves, text dims, paper, layout,  -->
                        <extent><measure unit="folio" quantity="314">314 folios, 8 flyleaves (ff. iv + 314 + iv)</measure>
                           <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm"><height>263</height><width>170</width></dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm"><height>244</height><width>140</width></dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="modern">Incomplete modern pencilled Arabic numerals on the upper-right corners of the a sides.</foliation>
                        <collation>Undetermined. <catchwords>Catchword throughout on the lower-left corners of the b sides.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>Handle with caution. Text in poor condition.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="64" n="mistara">Written in 1 column with 20 lines in the centres of the pages, with another 44 hemistichs in the surrounding margins, for 64 lines totalled. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">miṣṭārah</hi> hand guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="naskh" medium="ink">Written in <material>black</material> nasta‘līq script with <material>gold</material> headers.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc><summary></summary>
                     
                     <decoNote type="headpiece"><label>Illumination:</label>
                     </decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="marginal"><label>Ruling:</label>
                        
                     </decoNote>
                     
                  </decoDesc>
                  
                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     <list>
                        <item>The <locus from="ia" to="ivb">the right flyleaves </locus> bears a description of the manuscript and the work's author, signed by former owner <persName role="aut ins fmo">Sir Gore Ouseley</persName>, Hall Barn Park, <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1838-02">Feb. 1838</date>.</item>
                     </list>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc><binding notBefore="1768" notAfter="1799"><p>Probably bound in India then subsequently restored for former owner <persName role="aut ins fmo">Sir Gore Ouseley.</persName></p>
                     <p>Resewn on five recessed cords laced into the original boards. Edges trimmed, coloured red, with tall front-bead endbands sewn at head and tail in brown and white <material>silk</material>threads. Original boards of smooth, polished dark red goatskin <material>leather</material>, with internal doublures of the same.
                      New flyleaves added when restored, and the original board rebacked in British tan coloured calfskin <material>leather.</material></p>
                     <decoNote type="binding">Original boards blocked in <material>gold.</material> with scaloped central mandorlas, detached pendants, and corners featuring floral scrollwork designs. Rebacked spine fully paletted in <material>gold</material> and titled <q>KULIAT<lb/> I<lb/> SELMAN</q>. </decoNote>
                     
                     <condition>Handle binding with caution. In poor condition</condition>
                  </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <summary>Folios <locus>1a</locus> and 287a bear several <material>black</material> seal impressions, a round obliterated one, and two other legible impressions.</summary>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="scalloped_circle"><p><label>1:</label> A small round, scalloped seal impression, intaglio-carved in nasta‘līq script in three stacked lines, single ruled, with the name of a former owner or associate, <persName role="fmo seal">Farīdūn Aḥmad</persName>:</p>
                        <decoNote type="stamp" subtype="inscription"><p><q>بفریدون المستهر المعتمد احمد علی الله الصمد</q></p></decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="seal" unit="mm" subtype="diameter">
                           <dim type="diameter" unit="mm">~12</dim>
                        </dimensions></p></seal>
                     

                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="hexagon"><p><label>2:</label> A small elongated hexagonal seal impression, intaglio-carved in nasta‘līq script in three stacked lines, single-ruled, with the name of a former owner or associate, <persName role="fmo seal">Sayyid Muḥammad</persName>:</p>
                        <decoNote type="stamp" subtype="inscription"><p><q>غلام خاندان محمد سید استاء غبار اشرع احمد</q></p></decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="seal" unit="mm"><height>11.5</height><width>17</width></dimensions></p></seal>                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
